Aquatic engineering is where the engineer studies that of oceanography, and aquatic life in the area of fields.

{{Anthropology of kinship |concepts}}

The '''avunculate''', sometimes called '''avunculism''' or '''avuncularism''', is any social institution where a special relationship exists between an uncle and his [[Nephew and niece|sisters' children]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=F0aOAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT232&lpg=PT232&dq=Avunculate&source=bl&ots=rcsBD8kQCW&sig=jRTzPmnrdU1bZGwGeqtQC_8gYDQ&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Avunculate&f=false|title=The Routledge Encyclopedia of Social and Cultural Anthropology|last=Barnard|first=Alan|last2=Spencer|first2=Jonathan|date=2009-12-04|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135236403|language=en}}</ref> This relationship can be formal or informal, depending on the society. Early anthropological research focused on the association between the avunculate and [[Matrilineality|matrilineal]] descent, while later research has expanded to consider the avunculate in general society.

==Definition==
The term ''avunculate'' comes from the Latin ''[[wikt:avunculus|avunculus]],'' the maternal uncle.

The 1989 ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' defines "avunculate" as follows:
:"Avunculate. The special relationship existing in some societies between a maternal uncle and his sister's son; maternal uncles regarded as a collective body.
::1920 R. H. LOWIE Prim. Soc. v. 81 Ethnologists describe under the heading of avunculate the customs regulating in an altogether special way the relations of a nephew to his maternal uncle. Ibid. vii. 171 The Omaha are patrilineal now, but their having the avunculate proves that they once traced descent through the mother, for on no other hypothesis can such a usage be explained. ... "<ref>''Oxford English Dictionary''. Second Edition 1989. On-line version.</ref>

==Avunculocal societies==

An avunculocal society is one in which a married couple traditionally lives with the man's mother's eldest brother, which most often occurs in [[matrilineal]] societies. The [[Anthropology|anthropological]] term "avunculocal residence" refers to this convention, which has been identified in about 4% of the world's societies.<ref>Rosman, Abraham and Rubel, Paula G. ''The Tapestry of Culture: An Introduction to Cultural Anthropology''. Mcgraw-Hill College, 1995. ({{ISBN|0-07-053955-3}})</ref>

This pattern generally occurs when a man obtains his status, his job role, or his privileges from their nearest elder matrilineal male relative. When a woman's son lives near her brother, he is able to more easily learn how he needs to behave in the matrilineal role he has inherited.{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}

== Cultures with a formal avunculate ==

According to the [[Kazakhstan|Kazakh]] common law, the avunculate nephews could take anything from the relatives of the mother up to three times. In the [[Kyrgyz people|Kyrgyz]] past a nephew, at a feast at his maternal uncle or grandfather, could take any horse from their herd or any delicacy.<ref name="Zuev">Yu.Zuev, ''"Early Türks: Sketches of history and ideology"'', Almaty, Daik-Press, 2002, p. 30, {{Listed Invalid ISBN|9985-4-4152-9}}</ref>

In the [[Southwest United States]], the [[Apache]] tribe practices a form of this, where the uncle is responsible for teaching the children social values and proper behavior while inheritance and ancestry is reckoned through the mother's family alone. Modern day influences have somewhat but not completely erased this tradition.{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}

The [[Chamorros]] of the [[Mariana Islands]]<ref>Cunningham, Lawarence J. ''Ancient Chamorro Society''. Bess Press, 1992. ({{ISBN|1-880188-05-8}})</ref> and the [[Taíno people|Taíno]] of [[Turks and Caicos Islands]]<ref>Keegan, William F.  ''[http://www.flmnh.ufl.edu/caribarch/middle1999.htm Before Columbus: Caonabo’s Homeland]'', Middle Caicos Earthwatch Report, 1999.</ref> are examples of societies that have practiced avunculocal residence.

== Anthropology research ==

Research on the avunculate in the early 20th century focused on the association between the avunculate and patrilineal/matrilineal societies. [[Franz Boas]] categorized various avunculate arrangements based on the location of residence in 1922.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boas|first=Franz|date=1922-01-01|title=The Avunculate among the Vandau|jstor=660075|journal=American Anthropologist|volume=24|issue=1|pages=95–97|doi=10.1525/aa.1922.24.1.02a00150}}</ref> [[Henri-Alexandre Junod|Henri Alexandre Juno]] made the claim that the avunculate in the [[Tsonga people|Tsonga]] indicated that society had previously been matrilineal.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Ryder|first=J. W.|last2=Blackman|first2=M. B.|date=2016-09-14|title=The Avunculate: A Cross-Cultural Critique of Claude Levi-Strauss|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/106939717000500202|journal=Cross-Cultural Research|language=en|volume=5|issue=2|pages=97–115|doi=10.1177/106939717000500202}}</ref> [[Alfred Radcliffe-Brown]] identified the Tsonga (BaThonga) of [[Mozambique]], the [[Tonga]]ns of the Pacific, and the [[Nama people|Nama]] of Namibia as avunculate societies as early as 1924. He also expanded the concept to incorporate other family relationships.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://radicalanthropologygroup.org/sites/default/files/pdf/class_text_055.pdf|title=Structure and Function in Primitive Society|last=Radcliffe-Brown|first=Alfred|publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul|year=1952|isbn=|location=London|pages=15–31|quote=|via=}}</ref>

Later research moved beyond the issue of matrilinealism. [[Claude Lévi-Strauss]]   incorporating the avunculate into his "atom of kinship".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=S_DnQ82WpaoC&pg=PA140&lpg=PA140&dq=levi-strauss+avunculate&source=bl&ots=mEpT01_Hn3&sig=S9ezPAzyRvO5S8SwZSQAmnD7B1w&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=levi-strauss%20avunculate&f=false|title=Teaching Lévi-Strauss|last=Penner|first=Hans H.|date=1998-01-01|publisher=Scholars Press|isbn=9780788504907|language=en}}</ref> [[Jan N. Bremmer]] argued based on a survey of the Indo-European peoples that the avunculate is explained by the principle of education outside the (extended) family, and does not indicate matrilinealism.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bremmer|first=Jan|date=1976-01-01|title=EPRINTS-BOOK-TITLE|url=http://www.rug.nl/research/portal/publications/avunculate-and-fosterage(062fe6fa-623a-4676-b367-0575eba0ad5b).html|language=English}}</ref>

==Avunculate marriage==
{{Main|Avunculate marriage}}
In historical (not anthropological) terminology, an [[avunculate marriage]] is the marriage of a man with the daughter of his sister (not explicitly forbidden by the listings in [[Leviticus 18]]). In most cultures with avunculate customs in the sense used by anthropologists, such a marriage would violate incest taboos governing relations between members of the same [[matrilineality|matrilineal lineage]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}

